post_text:
The Minnesota Department of Health is developing a COVID Parent Screening Tool. This tool will provide guidance for when to keep your children home from school due to illness and/or COVID exposure. As soon as I receive this screening tool, it will be made available and should be used to screen your children for COVID symptoms. Prior to sending your children to school, a daily COVID screening must be conducted. Please see the link below for the most current COVID symptoms.

https://www.health.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/materials/symptoms.pdf

For any questions or concerns related to illness, please contact the health office at 507-836-6184 ext. 5111 for West and 4120 for Central. The health office will assist you with determining when your children may return to school. Please do not send your children or their siblings to school if they have been exposed to COVID or are exhibiting any COVID symptoms.

In Health,
Amanda Tentinger LSN PHN

Thrifty White Pharmacy will be providing a flu shot clinic at West Elementary on Wednesday, September 2nd from 10am to 2pm and Tuesday, September 8th from 8am to 12pm.

Please remember to bring your insurance card, as this vaccination is covered by most insurance plans. If you do not have proof of insurance or are uninsured, a cash payment will be required at the time of service. Cash price for ages 64 and under is $29.00. Cash price for the high dose vaccine, ages 65 and older is $58.99.

Strict social distancing guidelines will be followed. Remember to wear your mask and stay home if you are not feeling well.

post_text:
The MCC School Board wanted to give another update on the school mascot/mascot name after continued discussion at the regular August 10, 2020 school board meeting.

The Board reviewed the 198 community at large survey comments and wanted to reiterate that all of the data up to this point is only a piece of the process to gain as much information as possible.

Consultation with the marketing/advertising/graphics arts professional continues. It may take a couple months before they are available to meet with the board to gain additional information. That, along with the current focus of preparing a safe return to school for both students and staff under the approved model, the board has decided to suspend discussion/work on this topic at this time. Under the current circumstances, the board feels the focus of time should be spent on the more pressing matters. This does not diminish the concerns of this issue.

Good Morning,
Last night the school board decided to start the school year in the Hybrid Model which means all students will be in the school building each day with mandatory social distancing and face coverings. We can accomplish this due to the large square footage of our buildings and relatively small student population.

Registration starts today and will run from Tuesday August 11th through Sunday August 16th. All registration is online this year. Please log into your JMC parent portal to update your information.

Click on the link “register for 2020-2021” and fill out all forms (Free/Reduced, Health, and Residency) and questions for each child. Make sure to indicate if your child will be doing MCC Virtual Academy during the registration process.

If you do not remember your JMC username and password, please contact either the high school or elementary building administrative assistants during regular office hours. Thank you.

****Help in the comments****

post_text:
This afternoon, Gov. Walz along with MDE and MDH announced Minnesota’s Safe Learning Plan for the 2020-21 School Year. As a part of this plan, MDE and MDH have created Regional Support Teams to assist schools in determining the start to the school year.

The Safe Learning Plan uses a localized, data-driven approach that allows school districts to operate in a learning model that is responsive to the prevalence of COVID-19 cases in their communities.

MCC Schools will be consulting with the regional support team in the coming days to determine what the start of the year will look like. There is a possibility that the Elementary School may be in a different learning model than the High School. The data along with other factors will make this determination. Once a decision has been made, we will let everyone know right away. A definite date can not be given at this time.
Thank you for your continued patience.

post_text:
Dear MCC Family,
I wanted to send out a message to everyone that after much discussion with the prom committee, consisting of student, parent, teacher, and staff representatives of Murray County Central, the decision was made to cancel prom. Our current health situation and the fact that this prom would not be a “normal” prom were two of the biggest factors in the decision to cancel prom. There would not have been a dance this year due to the health requirements, and this is often the highlight for students. Many students felt that if we could not have a normal prom that they would rather not have prom. A discussion about after-prom and the money raised for after-prom was held. The after-prom committee which is a separate parent group/entity from the school district is going to discuss how to use the money raised for after-prom. While I know that this decision may be a disappointment for many, please know that it was made with much consideration from many perspectives. Thank you for your understanding.
Sincerely,
Jacob Scandrett- HS Principal

We have been inundated with emails, calls and texts voicing opinions on Rudy the Rebel! He is one popular guy!

As many of you know, this issue was raised several years ago and Rudy made some changes to his appearance. Rudy is once again a topic of discussion.

There will be no action taken on this matter tonight. The School Board has a Public Forum at every meeting and will again this evening. This is not a special meeting.

Rest assured the School Board and Administration strive to make the best decisions we can for our students and our communities.

To be an MCC Rebel, you have to be Respectful, Responsible and Ready to Learn. Be kind to each other.

post_text: A limited number of exam stations will reopen on Tuesday, May 19, 2020 at 8:00am for knowledge testing only. They will be running limited services, and have a safety plan established for all customers that will need to be adhered to. Only the following 15 exam stations will be open: Arden Hills, Anoka, Eagan, Plymouth, Rochester, Mankato, Marshall, Willmar, Detroit Lakes, St. Cloud, Brained, Duluth, Grand Rapids, Bemidji and St. Paul (knowledge testing only). Road tests will resume on Tuesday, May 26, 2020, by appointment only. Anyone without an appointment will be turned away. Once again there will be safety precautions put in place for those taking the road test that need to be followed. All appointments that were cancelled during the closure of exam stations will be notified through e-mail and text message on how to reschedule. They will have priority when re-scheduling their appointment, but will have to go to one of the above mentioned exam stations for the road test. Check the Minnesota State website for updates at https://dps.mn.gov/divisions/dvs/Pages/default.aspx.

post_text: Today our friend and co-worker, Pam Johnson, retired after 34 years of dedicated service to the school district. When we asked her what are some of the changes she has experienced over the years, she told us that when she started she had a Smith- CORONA typewriter (how ironic) and no computers in the building. We couldn’t have the party we planned, but we had a grand parade! Congratulations Pam, you will be missed. 💜

“BE THE LIGHT” – In honoring all of our students, staff, community and especially our 2020 seniors, the lights at the football complex will be turned on every Monday night at 8:20 pm (20:20 military time) for 20 minutes and 20 seconds.

To put an MCC uniqueness to this movement, we ask that all households turn their porch lights on during this same time. Let’s light up our communities! There is light at the end of this tunnel!

#REBELSTRONG, #BeTheLightMN (Please enjoy the lights from afar – No gathering is allowed)

post_text:
Women & Investing Informational Class
According to the US Bureau of Labor Statistics, 75% of our elderly poor are women. Despite advances, women remain less prepared to provide for their future financial security. Taking charge of your money is far easier than you can imagine and this course could be your first step. Learn about investing for your financial future and don’t wait for a crisis (divorce, illness, unemployment, or death) to spur you into action. From investment basics to evaluating your financial portfolio – we will talk about goal setting, risk and reward, and the tools to meet your goals. This is strictly a learning class and there will be no solicitations. Join Carla Goedtke & Katie Furth in the High School FACS Room on Wednesday, March 4, 2020 at 6:30 pm.

post_text: Under the new Graduated Driver License Law passed January 2015, students must now submit a drivers log verifying 50 hours of supervised driving time with a parent or guardian (15 of those hours must be nighttime driving). Parents attending a Point of Impact course are issued a parent certificate of completion which can be submitted to reduce the required supervised hours to 40 hours (15 of which still need to be nighttime driving). Behind the Wheel instruction DOES NOT count toward your hours. The 2020 Point of Impact course will be on Tuesday, March 10 from 8:00-9:30 pm in the MCC High School Auditorium (due to the Township Election Day, we cannot have any activity between 6:00-8:00 pm). This meeting is not mandatory and is for parents who have children enrolled in Behind the Wheel and Drivers Education Class.
text: Under the new Graduated Driver License Law passed January 2015, students must now submit a drivers log verifying 50 hours of supervised driving time with a parent or guardian (15 of those hours must be nighttime driving). Parents attending a Point of Impact course are issued a parent certificate of completion which can be submitted to reduce the required supervised hours to 40 hours (15 of which still need to be nighttime driving). Behind the Wheel instruction DOES NOT count toward your hours. The 2020 Point of Impact course will be on Tuesday, March 10 from 8:00-9:30 pm in the MCC High School Auditorium (due to the Township Election Day, we cannot have any activity between 6:00-8:00 pm). This meeting is not mandatory and is for parents who have children enrolled in Behind the Wheel and Drivers Education Class.
